Year = {2024},
Volume = {336},
Month = {OCT 1},
Abstract = {Wax gourd is an economically important crop species in the Cucurbitaceae
   family, with most commercial varieties being F 1 hybrid. It is
   time-consuming to obtain homozygous lines by traditional breeding
   methods. Doubled haploid (DH) technology is an efficient approach to
   accelerating breeding process, which has been successfully used in
   various crop. Nevertheless, little is known about the study of haploid
   induction in wax gourd. In this study, successful haploid induction was
   achieved by induced parthenogenesis using pollen irradiated in wax
   gourd. The pollen of cultivar `Rou2021 ` was irradiated with gamma ray
   at 100, 200, and 300 Gy. Female flowers were pollinated with irradiation
   pollen. The seeds extracted from the fruit were rescued on the culture
   medium for plant induction, and the ploidy level of the induced plants
   was determined by chromosome counting and flow cytometry. It showed that
   the number of fruit sets and induced plants was influenced by
   irradiation dose. Haploids were only obtained from lower irradiation
   doses at 100 Gy, with an efficiency of 0.13 to 0.14 \%. In addition,
   there were significant differences in phenotypes and anatomical
   structures between haploids and diploids. Our results demonstrated for
   the first time that haploids were successfully induced using gamma ray
   irradiated pollen in wax gourd. The findings are of great value for the
   utilization of heterozygosity and the aggregation of superior traits in
   a short time, which significantly accelerate the breeding process and
   genetic analysis of wax gourd.},
